  footnotes: []
english:
  title: Inscription Written After Reading the Record of Silkworm Head
  author: Park Eun
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Su Shi's prose commands all lands beneath heaven,
    Yet even the cosmos could not contain his towering spirit.
    Alas, that high renown itself became calamity—
    His verses gathered as evidence in court.

    Three years on Eastern Slope, gleaning broken tiles,
    Walking alone, watching his own shadow—who would shelter him?
    Only village women and peasant hags would laugh and say,
    "Once-grand wealth fades like a spring dream."

    The master bore it lightly, untroubled in his heart,
    Reclining high, finding solace in words alone.
    Now and then roused by mountain and water's call,
    He wandered forth on countless excursions.

    Beneath Red Cliff in autumn's seventh moon,
    The moonlight, full and radiant, blazed all the brighter.
    A single leaf-boat gliding through white dew,
    Seemed to fly with immortals through boundless space.
    Striking the gunwale, he sang in chorus with Cao Gong,
    While the mournful flute could not sustain the melody.
    Cup and guest passed back and forth without end,
    Cradled in embrace, forgetting when dawn broke.
    Then river-spirits aided his mighty words—
    Stanzas scattered to mortals and have endured.
    Even now his spirit soars through clouds,
    And I who once beheld it have sighed thrice over.

    This year fortune brought us to similar season,
    When past and present share one course.
    West Lake's marvel crowns Silkworm Head peak—
    Shall we not go there, my companions?
    Our three friends all laughed in agreement,
    Two attendants joined our pleasure.

    Setting out from Hemp Harbor with a lone skiff,
    The river swells in its springtime flood.
    Gentle waves rest, the wind blows soft—
    Fine scenery abounds for those who see it clear.
    In the chamber, Saewhae's brow held the highest joy,
    His hat discarded, unbound and free.
    One measure of wine brought forth five hundred characters,
    Each word a dragon and serpent, unbridled.

    On this day Saewhae inscribed Su Shi's Red Cliff Rhapsody.

    If there exists a kindred spirit in heaven's vault,
    Then the Immortal Su must surely marvel.
    At dusk we released our boat to strike the flowing light,
    Gazing west where azure waves stretched boundless.
    The boatman stayed his pole and spoke to us:
    "Beyond Silkworm Head the waters rage."
    We moored at a fishing village by merchant vessels,
    Where snores resonated like the roar of furnaces.
    Heaven itself seemed to cherish the bright moon,
    Scattering wisps of cloud across the Milky Way.
    Willows swayed like banners raised on high,
    Lanterns flickered bright as scattered stars.
    Sudden rain swept from the west with a cry,
    And great fish fled, splitting the waves in panic.

    We gathered close, passing cups with urgency,
    Delighting in your brilliant verses bursting forth.
    Recalling the old Commandant of Lingxin,
    Whose edicts were severe, whose talents seemed constrained—I almost fled!
    Raising cups to question the moon, calling Su the Immortal,
    We soared into emptiness, sprouting wings.
    As dawn approached, the waters swelled and churned,
    As if chaos had never yet been divided.

    Oar creaking through the mist, we pushed ahead—
    Distant grasses, long sandbars, cries of waterfowl.
    Willow catkins drifted at the ford through endless rain,
    While crystalline poems from the boat's depths gleamed brilliant.

    Returning, we lay abed ten days with closed doors,
    Recalling those old wanderings with wistful longing.
    Heroes pass away, heaven and earth grow old,
    How many years since the Immortal Su departed?
    Since ancient times human affairs have ever been thus—
    We three are each already beyond our prime.
    Do not let this joy scatter into emptiness,
    But when the spirit stirs, summon each other again with wine.
  footnotes:
    - Su Shi (蘇子瞻, 1037-1101), known as Su Dongpo, was a celebrated Song dynasty poet, painter, and official whose political involvement led to his persecution and exile.
    - The 'Red Cliff' (赤壁) refers to Su Shi's famous prose poem composed during his exile, reflecting on transience and finding meaning in nature.
    - Saewhae (士華) is the courtesy name of one of the three companions on this river excursion.
    - The reference to 'Silkworm Head' (蠶頭) appears to be a geographical location, likely a headland or mountain near their destination.
    - Cao Gong refers to Cao Cao (155-220), the ancient statesman-poet, evoking the literary tradition Su Shi participated in.
